\section{Introduction}

The nonequilibrium motions of small systems have been of great interest in the field of nonequilibrium statistical mechanics. Thermal fluctuations for such systems become very large and exhibit interesting  properties that are universal over different systems. The underlying principle for the universal properties is the fluctuation theorem (FT) which was first discovered for a deterministic system thermostatted so as to conserve the kinetic energy~\cite{evans93,evans94,gallavotti}.  The FT was later proven to hold for a wide class of stochastic systems~\cite{jarzynski,crooks,kurchan,lebowitz}. It deals with the thermal fluctuations of thermodynamic quantities produced persistently in time such as work and heat in nonequilibrium process. A typical form of the FT is given by $\langle e^{-\beta tw}\rangle=1$ where $w$ is the rate of the work production piled over a period $t$ for a nonequilibrium dynamics driven by a nonconservative force acting on the system initially prepared in equilibrium with the heat bath. $\beta$ is the inverse temperature $(k_B T)^{-1}$ for the Boltzmann constant $k_B$ and the temperature $T$ of the heat bath. The bracket denotes the average over all possible fluctuations. In order to investigate the FT and related issues, it is required to accurately deal with the probability distribution of the thermal fluctuations found in measuring the work produced in the nonequilibrium process.

Work and heat are path-dependent quantities. The thermal fluctuations of such quantities arise from many different paths (trajectories) along which the system evolves in time. One essentially needs the ensemble average over all paths from the past to the present, unlike the usual ensemble average of a state-dependent quantity over all states at a certain time. Theoretically the path integral theory was developed by Onsager and Mathlup based on the Langevin equation~\cite{onsager} and used to study the FT~\cite{kurchan}.    

In the experimental side, the fluctuations around the average value of a thermodynamic quantity for a small system become so predominant that they can be measurable with high accuracy by using modern technologies.  Interesting experiments confirming the FT were done for a colloidal particle in a moving optical trap~\cite{wang,trepagnier}, a molecule in the AFM pulled by an external force~\cite{hummer}, an electrical circuit driven by a small current~\cite{garnier}, and a harmonic oscillator under an external force~\cite{douarche,joubaud}, an RNA molecule unfolded and refolded by optical tweezers~\cite{liphardt,collin}, a rotating motor protein $\textrm{F}_1$-ATPase~\cite{hayashi}, and a breathing harmonic potential~\cite{pak}. 

An alternative approach to investigate large fluctuations for a small system is the molecular dynamics (MD). The MD deal with both a small system and a heat bath consisting of extremely many molecules by taking into account the interactions in detail among them and mimics an experiment as realistically as possible. It can play the role to bridge an experiment and a phenomenological theory such as the Langevin dynamics. The MD study was once accompanied in an experimental study of a colloidal particle in a moving optical trap~\cite{wang}. In our work, we investigate the motion of a colloidal particle in a liquid driven out of equilibrium by an external torque. We compare the results with those found by using the Langevin equation~\cite{kwon-ao-thouless,kwon,noh}. We expect the MD technique used in our work to be useful for future studies of other types of nonequilibrium sources. 


\section{Nonequilibrium Molecular dynamics}

The particles employed in the MD are divided into $N-1$ molecules of the liquid and the colloidal particle immersed in them. The liquid plays the role of a heat bath kept in equilibrium at a fixed temperature $T$. All particles are designed to interact with each other via the Lennard-Jones (LJ) potential:

where $\sigma$ and $\epsilon$ define the effective diameter and the energy intensity of the liquid molecules. In order to maintain the heat bath in equilibrium, we use the Langevin thermostat in which the same sort of dissipative and fluctuating forces as used for the Langevin equation are added~\cite{grest}. Then the equations of motion of the $i$-th molecule with the mass $m$, the position $\mathbf{x}_i$, and the velocity  $\mathbf{v}_i$ for $1\le i\le N-1$ are given  as  
\begin{eqnarray}
m\dot{\mathbf{v}}_i&=&-{\sum_{j(\neq i)}}\boldsymbol{\nabla}_iV_{\textrm{LJ}}(|\mathbf{x}_i-\mathbf{x}_j|; \sigma)-\gamma\mathbf{v}_i +\sqrt{\gamma \beta^{-1}}\boldsymbol{\xi}_i(t)\nonumber\\
&&~~-\boldsymbol{\nabla}_iV_{\textrm{LJ}}(|\mathbf{x}_i-\mathbf{x}|; \sigma')~,
\label{reservoir}
\end{eqnarray}
where $\mathbf{x}$ is the position of the colloidal particle. For the LJ potential between the colloidal particle and a liquid molecule, a different parameter $\sigma'$ is used. The energy intensity is set by the same value $\epsilon$ for all interactions.
The last two terms in the first line are given from the Langevin thermostat. The fluctuating force $\boldsymbol{\xi}_i$ is white noise with mean zero and the variance given by $\langle\xi_{ia}(t)\xi_{jb}(t')\rangle=2\delta_{ij}\delta_{ab}\delta(t-t')$ for $a, b=1,2,3$ denoting the components in 3 dimensions. The strength of the white noise, $\sqrt{\gamma \beta^{-1}}$, is related with the dissipation coefficient $\gamma$ and the inverse temperature $\beta$ of the heat bath. This relation is called the Einstein relation or the fluctuation-dissipation relation, which guarantees that the molecules reach an equilibrium with the Boltzmann distribution proportional to $e^{-\beta E_{\textrm{hb}}}$, where $E_{\textrm{hb}}$ is the total energy of the molecules in the heat bath given by $\sum_i m\mathbf{v}_i^2/2+\sum_{(i,j)} V_{\textrm{LJ}}(|\mathbf{x}_i-\mathbf{x}_j|;\epsilon,\sigma)$. The subscript $(i,j)$ denotes the pair of the molecules $i$ and $j$. The interaction energy between the liquid molecules and the colloidal particle is negligible in $E_{\textrm{hb}}\sim\mathcal{O}(N)$ so that the Boltzmann distribution is well maintained in a nonequilibrium process of the colloidal particle. The equilibrium heat bath can be guaranteed by supplying the heat bath with a sufficient number of molecules. 

