\section{Set-up for the simulations in equilibrium}

\subsection{Variables and parameters}

In our simulations, the liquid molecules and the colloidal particle are initially placed in a simulation box of size $L\times L \times L$. Periodic boundary conditions are imposed. Since the LJ potential is long-ranged, it will cost an enormous running-time to sum all the interactions. Instead we set a cut-off distance $r_c$ above which the LJ potential are truncated.  We adopt the parameters from the well established MD studies on the LJ liquids~\cite{thompson,cieplak}. The particle number density is set by $0.81\sigma^{-3}$ and the temperature by $1.1\epsilon/k_B$ for the Boltzmann constant $k_B$, which was found to represent a compressed liquid above the melting temperature. We use $r_c=2.2\sigma$ for the interactions among the liquid molecules, $r_c=2.2\sigma'$ for the interactions between the colloidal particle and a liquid molecule. Above $r_c$, the LJ potential was found to be negligible compared to thermal energies.

We introduce dimensionless variables and parameters used for the simulation. We rescale $M/m\to M$, $\mathbf{x}/\sigma=\mathbf{x}$, $\beta^{-1}/\epsilon\to \beta^{-1}$, $t/\sqrt{m\sigma^2/\epsilon}\to t$. Then $m$, $\epsilon$, and $\sigma$ are set to unity, and  $\sigma'/\sigma$ to $\sigma'$. Given the above choice of temperature, $\beta^{-1}$ goes to $1.1$. In this rescaling, $V_{\textrm{LJ}}(|\mathbf{x}_i-\mathbf{x}_j|/\sigma;1)$ goes to $V_{\textrm{LJ}}(|\mathbf{x}_i-\mathbf{x}_j|; 1)$ and $V_{\textrm{LJ}}(|\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{x}_i|/\sigma; \sigma'/\sigma)$ to $V_{\textrm{LJ}}(|\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{x}_i|; \sigma')$. We also change $\gamma/\sqrt{m\epsilon/\sigma^2}\to \gamma$, $k/(\epsilon/\sigma^2)\to k$. $\kappa_1$ and $\kappa_2$ are set in the unit of $\epsilon/\sigma^2$ as $k$. The white noises having the unit of $t^{-1/2}$ are rescaled as $(m\sigma^2/\epsilon)^{-1/4}\boldsymbol{\xi_i}\to \boldsymbol{\xi_i}$. All changed variables and parameters become dimensionless. In the following we will use the dimensionless variables and parameters.

$\gamma$ is not a real coefficient of the friction exerted in the liquid, but a mathematical parameter of the Langevin thermostat. Then we can choose $\gamma=1$ as far as the temperature of the heat bath is fixed from the Einstein relation, so the random force is written as $\beta^{-1/2}\boldsymbol{\xi}_i$ in Eq.~(\ref{reservoir}). 

\subsection{Overdamped limit}

The experimental condition in most cases is consistent with the overdamped limit where the inertial effect is negligible. From the point of view based on the Langevin dynamics, the equation of motion of the colloidal particle corresponding to Eq.~(\ref{colloidal}) is given as  $M\dot{\mathbf{v}}=\mathbf{f}-\gamma_c\mathbf{v}+\sqrt{\gamma_c\beta^{-1}}\boldsymbol{\xi}$, where $\gamma_c$ is the coefficient of the friction exerting on the colloidal particle in a viscous liquid and $\boldsymbol{\xi}$ is the same Gaussian noise as in Eq.~(\ref{reservoir}). In the overdamped limit, the fast-varying velocity relaxes more rapidly than the slowly-varying position. For $\mathbf{f}=-k\mathbf{x}$, the relaxation time of the velocity is known to be $M/\gamma_c$, and that of the position to be $\gamma_c/k$. Then the criterion for the overdamped limit can be given by $M/\gamma _c\ll\gamma_c/k$. Mathematically, one can have the overdamped limit either by small $M$ or by large $\gamma_c$. Since $M$ is very large for a real colloidal particle, compared to liquid molecules, $\gamma_c$ should be large enough for the overdamped limit. However, $\gamma_c$ is not a direct control parameter in the MD simulation. Instead, we can obtain the overdamped limit to a good extent by increasing the radius $\sigma'$ of the cross section expecting $\gamma_c\propto \sigma'$. In hydrodynamics, where the liquid is regarded as a continuous media, the Stokes law holds as $\gamma_c=6\pi\eta R$ for the viscosity $\eta$ and the radius of the colloidal particle $R$. In the MD simulation, $R$ should be replaced by the radius of the cross section for the colloidal particle and a liquid particle. Since the particles are not hard spheres with well-defined radii, we expect $R\propto \sigma'$, hence $\gamma_c\propto\sigma'$. 

In this work we choose $M=10$ and $\sigma'=1.5$, which corresponds to the colloidal particle 10 times heavier and 2 times larger than the liquid molecules. Under periodic boundary conditions, the box size must be large enough to avoid possible unrealistic hydrodynamic interactions between the colloidal particle and its periodic replicas. For our simulations, we set the size of $L=21.46$, satisfying $\sigma'/L < 1/10$. Then 8,000 molecules are employed in simulations.  

\subsection{Simulations for equilibrium}

We run the simulations in discrete steps $n$ for $1\le n\le N_T$ with an interval $\Delta t$ for which the differential equations in Eqs.~(\ref{reservoir}) and (\ref{colloidal}) are changed into difference equations for states between steps. We will have $N_S$ samples each of which consists of $N_T$ simulations where we use random sampling out of the sets of discrete random numbers used from the Langevin thermostat in Eq.~(\ref{reservoir}), $\{\eta_{ia,n}\}$ for $\eta_{ia,n}=\int _{t_n}^{t_n+\Delta t}dt\xi_{ia}(t)$, with mean zero and  variance $\langle\eta_{ia,n}^2\rangle=2\Delta t$. The average values of work and heat productions are found as

