The dynamics is shown to be stable so as to reach a new steady state if $\mathsf{F}$ is positive-definite ~\cite{kwon-ao-thouless,kwon}, i.e., $\textrm{Re}(k\pm\sqrt{\kappa_1\kappa_2})>0$. If $\mathsf{F}$ is symmetric with $\kappa_1=\kappa_2$, the force is conservative. Then the new steady-state distribution is also Boltzmann associated with the potential energy  $1/2(kx^2 +ky^2+2\kappa_1 xy)$. If $\mathsf{F}$ is asymmetric with $\kappa_1\neq\kappa_2$, the force is nonconservative and the colloidal particle reaches a nonequilibrium steady state. 

The nonequilibrium steady state is characterized by the incessant productions of work and heat found from Eq.~(\ref{ave_production}). Since $\langle E\rangle$ does not change in the steady state, the work and heat productions become the same asymptotically for large $t$. In Fig.~\ref{fig3}, we observe that $\langle W\rangle\rangle/t$ and $\langle Q\rangle/t$ converges the same value as time goes. From a recent study for the same system via the overdamped Langevin equation~\cite{kwon}, one can get $\langle W\rangle/t\to2[(\kappa_1-\kappa_2)/2]^2 \beta^{-1}/(k\gamma_c)$ as $t\to \infty$. In our dimensionless units, it is equal to $2.2/\gamma_c$ for $k=\kappa_1=-\kappa_2=1$, $\sigma'=1.5$, and $\beta^{-1}=1.1$. From the data in Fig.~\ref{fig3}, we estimate $\gamma_c\simeq 29$.

