\section{Work and heat distributions: Fluctuation Theorem}

The repeated measurements of work and heat produced during a period $t$ yield large fluctuations around the average values. The FT is a mathematical principle about the distribution functions for such fluctuations for the thermodynamics quantities accumulated in time. It is convenient to consider the rates of work and heat, $w=W/t$ and $q=Q/t$, since $\langle W\rangle$ and $\langle Q\rangle$ increase linearly in large $t$, as seen in the last section. 

We obtain the distribution functions for $w$ and $q$, that are found as $t^{-1}\sum_n\dot{W}_{ns}$ and $t^{-1}\sum_n\dot{Q}_{ns}$, respectively, from $10^5$-$10^6$ samples of the MD simulations; see Eq.~(\ref{ave_production}). 
Fig.~\ref{fig5} shows the distribution functions for $w$ and $q$. The two distributions show clear difference even for large $t$ where $\langle w\rangle$ becomes equal to $\langle q\rangle$.

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics*[width=\columnwidth]{fig5.eps}
\caption{(Color online) The distribution functions for (a) work and (b) heat produced for various times. The centers of the distributions approaches to the positive asymptotic value as in Fig.~\ref{fig3}. The distributions for the two quantities show clear difference even for large $t$. The distribution for $w<0$ shows that the thermodynamic second law for work can be violated in individual events.}
\label{fig5}
\end{figure}


In previous works, we intensively investigated the distribution function for $w$ by means of the generating function $g(\lambda)=\langle e^{-\lambda\beta tw}\rangle$~\cite{kwon,noh}. We confirmed the so-called Gallavotti-Cohen symmetry, $g(\lambda)=g(1-\lambda)$, which is known to be another representation of the FT. $g(\lambda)$ is defined for $\lambda_-<\lambda<\lambda_+$ for $\lambda_-<0$ and $\lambda_+>0$ with the relation $\lambda_+=1-\lambda_-$ from the Gallavotti-Cohen symmetry. $\lambda_{\pm}$ depends on time $t$. We found $g(\lambda)$ to be divergent at $\lambda=\lambda_{\pm}$. We found this divergence to lead to an exponential decay for each tail of the work distribution, written as 
$|w|^{-\alpha} e^{t\lambda_- w}$ for $w\to\infty$ and $|w|^{-\alpha} e^{t\lambda_+ w}$ for $w\to-\infty$.  Depending on the form of $\mathsf{F}$ and time $t$, we found the three types of tail behaviors characterized by $\alpha=0~,1/2,~2$, respectively. The first type occurs for our case while the other two occur for unequal diagonal elements of $\mathsf{F}$, corresponding to an anisotropic optical trap. Fig.~\ref{fig6} shows a clear view of the exponential decay in the distribution function for work, which is the symptom of the first type. The estimated values of $\lambda_{\pm}$ are shown to confirm the expected Gallavotti-Cohen symmetry. 

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics*[width=\columnwidth]{fig6.eps}
\caption{(Color online) The semi-log plots of the distribution functions for work rate $w$ for various $t$ show exponential decays in both tails. 
In the inset, the table for the values of $\lambda_{\pm}$ from the slopes of the tails for various $t$ shows the Gallavotti-Cohen symmetry, $\lambda_++\lambda_-=1$.}
\label{fig6}
\end{figure}


The integral FT  (IFT) for a time-accumulated thermodynamic quantity $R$ is written as $\langle e^{-\beta R}\rangle=1$. $R$ is associated with a specific initial distribution with which the system is provided before a nonequilibrium source is turned on~\cite{seifert,esposito}. Using the Jensen's inequality, $\langle e^{-x}\rangle\ge1-\langle x\rangle$, we have an inequality $\langle R\rangle \ge 0$. $R$ can be $T\Delta S_{\textrm{tot}}$ for general initial distributions where $\Delta S_{\textrm{tot}}$ is the total entropy change of the system and the heat path. Then the inequality is the second law of thermodynamics for the entropy of the closed system. The entropy of the system is defined as $-k_B \ln P(\mathbf{x},t)$ (in the overdamped limit). It is difficult to confirm the FT for $\Delta S_{\textrm{tot}}$ in the MD simulations as well as in experiments since the probability distribution is not a directly observable quantity. If an initial distribution is Boltzmann and the nonequilibrium source is a nonconservative force, as in our case, then $R$ can be the work production $W=tw$. Then the inequality $\langle W\rangle\ge 0$ holds. In the presence of a time-dependent protocol, that is not our case, $R=W_{irr}=W-\Delta F$ and the corresponding inequality is $\langle W_{irr}\rangle\ge 0$. The IFT for work was first found by Jarzynski~\cite{jarzynski}. This inequality is another form of the second law for nonequilibrium work. For a uniform initial distribution, that can be obtained at infinite temperature, $R=Q$. In real experiments, however, the FT for heat is hardly observable. 

The detailed FT (DFT) is written as $P_{\textrm{F}}(R)/P_{\textrm{B}}(-R)=e^{\beta R}$. $P_{\textrm{F}}$ ($P_{\textrm{B}}$) denotes the distribution of $R$ for the forward (backward) process for a given (backward) change of the protocol in time. The DFT guarantees the IFT, but the converse is not always true. There is a special requirement for the DFT~\cite{esposito}. One good example is $R=W$ for nonequilibrium dynamics starting from the equilibrium distributions, which is our case. 

All the theoretical derivations for the FT are based on the Langevin dynamics or the master equation. We expect the FT to hold in the MD simulations as good as in the real experiments~\cite{wang,trepagnier,hummer,garnier,douarche,joubaud,liphardt,collin,hayashi,pak}. Moreover, we have shown the MD simulations to agree well with the Langevin dynamics. From the IFT, we expect $\langle w\rangle>0$. However, Fig.~\ref{fig5} shows that the IFT (the second law) can be violated in individual events. We do not test the IFT for work because of severe sampling errors in measuring the exponentiated quantity $e^{-\beta t w}$. Instead we confirm the DFT for $w$. In our case with no time-dependent protocol, we can drop the subscripts $F$, $B$ and expect the DFT as

