As $t$ increases, the effect of the initial distribution decays exponentially in time. Then one might expect that heat becomes equivalent with work and the DFT holds for heat. However, Fig.~\ref{fig6}(b) shows that it is not the case even for large $t$. The two path-dependent quantities are related by the first law as $Q=W-\Delta E$. For large $t$, $W$ and $Q$ are only equivalent in average. By rare chances, however, $\Delta E$ can be comparable to work and heat for unbound state with $0\le E< \infty$, as in our case. If an initial (final) state is found from the tail far from the center of the distribution, $\Delta E$ can be negatively (positively) large so that it can give significant influence on the positive (negative) tail of the heat distribution. Recent works revealed that the initial memory everlasts in the positive tail of the heat distribution~\cite{farago,jslee}. The so-called boundary effect on the DFT for heat due to $\Delta E$ was investigated in recent works~\cite{vanzon,puglisi,jd,kwangmoo}. 
Fig.~\ref{fig7}(b) shows the violation of the DFT for heat even if $t$ increases. For large $t$, the slope of $f(q)$ near the center of the distribution seems to go to unity while the tails remain nonlinear, as shown for the other nonequilibrium system~\cite{vanzon,kwangmoo}. 
\section{summary}

We investigate the motion of a colloidal particle in a liquid driven by a nonconservative force producing a torque by using the MD simulation. The liquid composed of many molecules are designed to play the role of a heat bath at a fixed temperature by using the Langevin thermostat. The colloidal particle and the liquid molecules are designed to interact with each other via the LJ potentials. 

We mimic an experiment in the overdamped limit due a large friction for which we assign larger values of mass and size for the colloidal particle than those of the liquid molecules. We estimate the values of the friction coefficient $\gamma_{\textrm{c}}$ originated from the Langevin equation from three methods: the equilibrium and nonequilibrium autocorrelation functions for position in time and the asymptotic production rates of work and heat for infinite $t$. The three values are found to be identical in high accuracy and to hold the Stokes law, which assure us of the reliability of our MD simulations.  

After running the simulations for a sufficiently long time in the absence of any nonconservative force for the colloidal particle to reach an equilibrium state, we turn on a nonconservative force with $\kappa_1\neq\kappa_2$ and perform measurements for work and heat produced for time $t$. From $10^5$-$10^6$ samples due to random numbers used for the Langevin thermostat, we find the distribution functions for work and heat. The distribution functions for work for various $t$ are found to  decay exponentially for the both tails of the distribution, from which we confirm the Gallavotti-Cohen symmetry. We also confirm the DFT to hold for work, but not for heat, as expected for nonequilibrium processes starting initially from equilibrium states. We observe that the second law of thermodynamics can be violated in individual events while satisfied in average. We discuss the boundary effect on the heat distribution to yield the violation of the DFT for heat.

In future we will investigate the nonequilibrium motion beyond the overdamped limit by increasing the mass of the colloidal particle or decreasing the friction coefficient. We are also interested in the MD study on other examples driven by different sources of nonequilibrium.  


